  "opinion": "As someone who’s spent most of my life in a world where science feels distant and intimidating, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived experience. Growing up in Kansas City as the daughter of a person with a bachelor’s degree and someone with a lower secondary education, I was exposed to a mix of encouragement and subtle biases. My parents didn’t push me into STEM fields, but they also didn’t steer me away from them. Still, in my part-time work as a hairdresser, I’ve noticed how few women are in leadership roles in science, especially in fields like engineering or physics. I’m anxious about the future, and I worry that without intentional efforts to bridge this gap, fewer girls and women will feel empowered to pursue science. The gap isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who feels welcome, who feels capable, and who gets the chance to thrive. For me, addressing it means creating spaces where curiosity isn’t punished by stereotypes. In my small community, I’ve seen how mentorship and inclusive classrooms can make a difference. But it starts with listening, not just fixing. I’m a woman with a lower secondary education, so I know how hard it is to break into a field that often assumes you have more advanced knowledge. We need to stop treating science as something only for those who’ve already been taught to think like scientists. Instead, we should focus on early exposure, like bringing hands-on experiments into schools or supporting women in STEM through community programs. The anxiety I feel when I think about the future makes me want to do something concrete. Maybe it’s helping a girl in my neighborhood see herself in a scientist, or sharing my own experiences to show that you don’t have to be a genius to start exploring science. The gap isn’t something we can fix overnight, but it’s something we can address with patience and care.",
